        introduction: "The Fougères to Mont-Saint-Michel journey links two iconic monuments of the Breton Marches — two fortresses separated by 50 km that each embody medieval power and ingenuity. Fougères is the land guardian with its colossal fortress of thirteen towers, considered Europe's largest medieval castle, built from the 11th to 15th centuries to defend the eastern border of the Duchy of Brittany. Victor Hugo and Balzac both used it as a setting for their novels. Mont-Saint-Michel, at the other end, is the maritime guardian — a rocky islet of 900 metres circumference topped by a Benedictine abbey founded in 708, rising 157 metres above the bay. Named the Wonder of the Western World, Mont-Saint-Michel has been a UNESCO World Heritage Site since 1979 and welcomes over 3 million visitors annually, making it France's most visited site outside Paris. The bay features some of Europe's highest tides (up to 15 metres at equinox spring tides), creating a natural spectacle without equal. The taxi is used by tourists combining Fougères Castle with the Mont, families on holiday and travellers wanting direct transport to the Mont.",
        itineraire: "Your driver leaves Fougères north-westward on the D155, crossing the Breton Marches countryside of rolling hills and hedgerow-bordered pastures. You pass near the Villecartier state forest, marking the transition to the low-lying bay lands. Joining the D797 towards Mont-Saint-Michel, the landscape changes dramatically: hills give way to polders — vast flat expanses reclaimed from the sea since the 19th century, growing sandy carrots, Roscoff onions and cauliflowers. On clear days, Mont-Saint-Michel's silhouette appears gradually on the horizon, first as a dark point between sky and land, then increasingly majestic as you approach. Arrival is at the Caserne shuttle car park, from where free shuttles or the pedestrian bridge-walkway (opened 2014) take you to the Mont. Your driver drops you as close as possible to the entrance. The journey takes 35 minutes normally, up to 50 minutes in peak summer or during spring tides.",
        conseils: "Visiting Mont-Saint-Michel takes at least 2-3 hours: the Grande Rue climb, the abbey (about 11 euros, free under 26 EU), ramparts, cloister and the Marvel. Wear comfortable shoes as the access is steeply uphill. Spring tides, with dates published in advance, offer an exceptional spectacle when the sea completely surrounds the rock — most impressive at the March and September equinoxes with 14-15 metre tidal ranges. If you wish to cross the bay on foot, a licensed guide is essential due to quicksand and the speed of incoming tides. La Mere Poulard restaurant at the Mont entrance is world-famous for its wood-fire souffleed omelettes (tradition since 1888, budget 40-60 euros per person). The return Mont-Saint-Michel to Fougères is available at the same rate.",
        comparaisonTransport: "There is no direct public transport between Fougères and Mont-Saint-Michel. The bus route requires going via Pontorson then a shuttle, totalling 1h30-2h. Carpooling is virtually non-existent on this route. The TaxiNeo taxi at 60 — 80 euros is the only direct and comfortable option in 35 minutes. For 3-4 passengers (15-27 euros per person), very reasonable for a door-to-door transfer to France's most visited site outside Paris.",
